Container service networking.

A task can use one of four network modes, but for almost all new workloads the answer is the v-p-c networking mode. In that mode, each task gets its own elastic network interface and private address inside your virtual private cloud; it's required for Fargate and the default on instances.

The legacy bridge and host modes exist only for the instance launch type, and there's a none mode for fully isolated tasks. The big payoff of per-task networking is that each task carries its own security group and address, so you treat tasks like small instances on the network and never need dynamic port mapping.

For load balancing, you attach the service to a target group, and the service registers tasks as they launch and deregisters them as they stop, respecting the draining delay so in-flight requests finish.
